    explanation: "The distinction between void and voidable contracts is fundamental to contract law. A void contract is one that was never legally valid from the start — it has no legal effect, and neither party can enforce it. A voidable contract is initially valid and enforceable but can be canceled (rescinded) by one party due to specific legal defects.\n\nA contract may be void because: it involves an illegal purpose, one party lacks legal capacity (like a person declared mentally incompetent), it's impossible to perform, or essential elements are missing. A void contract cannot be ratified or made valid.\n\nA contract may be voidable because: one party was a minor (who can choose to honor or void the contract upon reaching majority), it was entered under duress or undue influence, it was based on fraud or misrepresentation, or there was a mutual mistake about a material fact. The party with the right to void the contract can choose to either enforce it or rescind it.",
