    definition: "A legal action requiring a person under arrest to be brought before a judge to determine if detention is lawful.",
    explanation: "Habeas corpus (Latin for 'you shall have the body') is one of the most fundamental legal protections against unlawful detention. It allows a person who is imprisoned or detained to petition a court to examine whether their detention is lawful. If the court finds the detention unlawful, it orders the person's release.\n\nThe right of habeas corpus is protected by the U.S. Constitution (Article I, Section 9), which states that the privilege of the writ of habeas corpus shall not be suspended except in cases of rebellion or invasion. It is considered a cornerstone of individual liberty and a check on government power.\n\nHabeas corpus petitions are commonly used by prisoners challenging the constitutionality of their conviction or sentence, immigration detainees challenging their detention, and individuals held in military or emergency detention. The petition must show that the detention violates the Constitution, a federal law, or a treaty.",
