    explanation: "Perjury is the deliberate act of lying or making false statements while under oath or in a sworn document. It's a criminal offense because the integrity of the legal system depends on truthful testimony and accurate sworn statements.\n\nTo prove perjury, the prosecution must show: the person was under oath or made a sworn statement, the statement was false, the person knew the statement was false (not merely mistaken), and the false statement was material (relevant to the proceeding). Honest mistakes or differences of opinion are not perjury.\n\nPerjury is typically charged as a felony, punishable by imprisonment and fines. Related offenses include subornation of perjury (inducing someone else to commit perjury) and making false statements to federal officials (which doesn't require being under oath). Prosecutors are selective about charging perjury — it's difficult to prove intent and can be hard to distinguish from genuine memory lapses.",
