    term: "Standing",
    category: "Legal Process",
    definition: "The legal right to bring a lawsuit. A party must show they have been directly affected by the issue.",
    explanation: "Standing (or 'locus standi') is a threshold requirement that determines whether a party has the right to bring a lawsuit in court. Without standing, a court will dismiss the case regardless of its merits. Standing ensures courts decide actual controversies rather than hypothetical questions.\n\nTo establish standing in federal courts, a plaintiff must demonstrate three elements (from the Lujan v. Defenders of Wildlife case): injury in fact (a concrete, particularized injury that is actual or imminent), causation (the injury is fairly traceable to the defendant's action), and redressability (a favorable court decision would likely remedy the injury).\n\nStanding requirements serve important functions: they prevent courts from issuing advisory opinions, ensure that cases are brought by parties with a genuine stake in the outcome, and maintain the separation of powers by limiting judicial involvement in political questions.",
    exampleClause: "Plaintiff has standing to bring this action because Plaintiff suffered direct financial harm as a result of Defendant's breach, and the requested relief would remedy that harm.",
