    explanation: "Subrogation is a legal doctrine that allows one party (typically an insurance company) to 'step into the shoes' of another party to pursue a legal claim. When an insurer pays a claim to its insured, the insurer acquires the right to pursue the party who caused the loss to recover the amount paid.\n\nFor example, if your car is damaged by another driver's negligence and your insurance company pays for the repairs, the insurance company can then pursue the at-fault driver (or their insurer) to recover the payment. This prevents the insured from receiving double recovery and ensures the at-fault party ultimately bears the cost.\n\nSubrogation can be conventional (arising from contract), legal/equitable (arising by operation of law), or statutory (created by statute). Insurance policies typically include subrogation clauses requiring the insured to cooperate with the insurer's subrogation efforts and not to do anything that would prejudice the insurer's rights.",
