    explanation: "Usury is the practice of charging interest on a loan at a rate that exceeds the legal maximum. Usury laws exist to protect borrowers from predatory lending and have been part of legal systems for thousands of years.\n\nUsury limits vary significantly by state. Some states set specific maximum rates (often 10-18% for consumer loans), while others tie limits to market rates. Some types of lenders (like banks and credit unions) may be exempt from state usury laws under federal preemption. The type of loan also matters — different limits may apply to consumer loans, commercial loans, mortgages, and credit cards.\n\nThe consequences of usury vary by state: the lender may forfeit all interest, forfeit the entire loan amount, or face criminal penalties. Some states use a 'savings clause' approach, limiting recovery to the legal maximum rather than voiding the entire transaction. Payday lending and some fintech lending arrangements have raised modern usury concerns.",
