    term: "Adhesion Contract",
    category: "Contract Law",
    definition: "A standardized contract offered on a take-it-or-leave-it basis by a party with superior bargaining power, leaving the other party no ability to negotiate terms.",
    explanation: "Adhesion contracts are everywhere in modern life. When you sign up for a streaming service, download an app, or rent a car, you're almost certainly agreeing to an adhesion contract. These agreements are drafted entirely by one party (usually a corporation) and presented to the other party (usually a consumer) without any opportunity to negotiate.\n\nWhile adhesion contracts are generally enforceable, courts scrutinize them more carefully than negotiated agreements. If a term is found to be unconscionable — meaning it's so one-sided that it shocks the conscience — a court may refuse to enforce that specific provision. Courts pay special attention to terms that are hidden in fine print, that waive important rights, or that heavily favor the drafting party.\n\nThe key legal question with adhesion contracts is whether the weaker party had meaningful choice. If alternative products or services were available, courts are more likely to enforce the terms. But if the contract involves an essential service with no real alternatives, courts may apply greater scrutiny.",
    exampleClause: "By clicking 'I Agree,' you acknowledge that you have read, understood, and agree to be bound by all terms and conditions of this Agreement. These terms are non-negotiable and constitute the entire agreement between you and the Company.",
