    explanation: "Anti-assignment clauses are common in commercial contracts, leases, and service agreements. They protect parties from suddenly finding themselves in a contractual relationship with an unknown or unwanted third party.\n\nThese clauses serve several important purposes. They ensure that the original parties maintain control over who performs obligations and receives benefits under the contract. In service contracts, for example, a client may have chosen a specific provider based on their expertise and reputation — an assignment could substitute a less qualified party.\n\nThe enforceability of anti-assignment clauses varies by context. Under the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC), clauses that prohibit assignment of the right to receive payment are generally unenforceable. In real estate, many jurisdictions limit restrictions on assignment. However, in most commercial contracts between businesses, anti-assignment clauses are fully enforceable.",
