    definition: "A contract in which both parties exchange mutual promises to perform, creating reciprocal obligations that each party is bound to fulfill.",
    explanation: "A bilateral contract is the most common type of contract. It's formed when two parties each make a promise to the other. For example, when you agree to buy a car, you promise to pay the purchase price and the dealer promises to deliver the vehicle. Both sides have obligations.\n\nThis contrasts with a unilateral contract, where only one party makes a promise in exchange for the other party's performance (not a promise). A classic example of a unilateral contract is a reward offer: 'I'll pay $500 to whoever finds my lost dog.' The offeror promises payment, but no one is obligated to search.\n\nIn bilateral contracts, both parties are bound from the moment they exchange promises. If either party fails to perform, the other can sue for breach of contract. The mutual exchange of promises itself constitutes the consideration needed to make the contract binding.",
