    category: "Contract Law",
    definition: "The legal ability of a person or entity to enter into a binding contract. Minors, mentally incapacitated persons, and intoxicated individuals may lack legal capacity.",
    explanation: "Capacity is one of the essential elements required for a valid contract. Without capacity, a contract may be void or voidable. The law recognizes several categories of persons who may lack capacity to contract.\n\nMinors (persons under 18 in most states) can enter into contracts, but those contracts are generally voidable at the minor's option. This means the minor can choose to honor or disaffirm the contract, but the adult party is bound. There are exceptions for necessities like food, shelter, and medical care.\n\nMentally incapacitated persons may lack capacity if they cannot understand the nature and consequences of the transaction. Courts apply different tests — some focus on cognitive ability, others on whether the person can act reasonably. Contracts made during lucid intervals may be enforceable.\n\nIntoxicated persons may void contracts if they were so impaired they couldn't understand the transaction, and the other party knew or should have known of their condition.",
