    category: "Legal Process",
    definition: "A lawsuit filed by one or more representative plaintiffs on behalf of a larger group (class) of people who have similar legal claims against the same defendant.",
    explanation: "Class action lawsuits allow a large number of people with similar claims to sue as a group. This mechanism is essential when individual claims would be too small to justify separate lawsuits, but the aggregate harm is significant.\n\nTo proceed as a class action, the case must meet specific requirements under Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 23 (or equivalent state rules). The class must be so numerous that joining all members individually is impractical (numerosity). There must be questions of law or fact common to the class (commonality). The representative plaintiffs' claims must be typical of the class (typicality). And the representatives must adequately protect the interests of the class (adequacy).\n\nClass actions are common in consumer fraud, securities fraud, product liability, employment discrimination, and data breach cases. If the class wins, damages are distributed among all class members, often through a claims process. Class members who don't opt out are bound by the judgment.",
