    definition: "A legal doctrine that allocates fault among all parties involved in an accident or injury based on their respective degrees of negligence, reducing damages proportionally.",
    explanation: "Comparative negligence replaced the harsh traditional rule of contributory negligence (where any fault by the plaintiff barred all recovery) in most states. Under comparative negligence, a plaintiff's damages are reduced by their percentage of fault.\n\nThere are two main forms. Under pure comparative negligence (used in about 13 states including California and New York), a plaintiff can recover even if they're 99% at fault — they'd just receive 1% of their damages. Under modified comparative negligence (used in about 33 states), a plaintiff can recover only if their fault is below a threshold, typically 50% or 51%.\n\nFor example, if you're in a car accident and suffer $100,000 in damages, but the jury finds you 30% at fault, you'd recover $70,000 under either system. But if you were 55% at fault, you'd recover $45,000 under pure comparative negligence but nothing under a 50% modified system.",
