    definition: "Indirect losses that result from a breach of contract, beyond the direct value of the contract itself — such as lost profits, lost business opportunities, or damage to reputation.",
    explanation: "Consequential damages (also called special or indirect damages) are losses that don't flow directly from the breach itself but from the secondary consequences of the breach. They're distinguished from direct damages, which represent the value of the performance that was promised but not delivered.\n\nFor example, if a supplier fails to deliver parts on time, the direct damages might be the cost of finding replacement parts. The consequential damages could include the buyer's lost profits from being unable to manufacture and sell their products, penalties the buyer incurred from their own customers, and increased costs of emergency sourcing.\n\nConsequential damages are recoverable only if they were reasonably foreseeable at the time the contract was formed (the rule from Hadley v. Baxendale). Many commercial contracts include clauses that limit or exclude consequential damages, which are generally enforceable between sophisticated business parties.",
