    term: "Constructive Notice",
    category: "Legal Principle",
    definition: "A legal presumption that a person has knowledge of facts because those facts are publicly available or properly recorded, even if the person didn't actually know them.",
    explanation: "Constructive notice is a fundamental concept in property law, corporate law, and many other legal areas. It means the law treats you as if you know something, even if you actually don't, because the information was available through public records or other established channels.\n\nThe most common example is recorded real estate documents. When a deed, mortgage, or lien is recorded with the county recorder's office, everyone is deemed to have constructive notice of that document. A buyer who fails to check the public records can't later claim they didn't know about an existing mortgage on the property.\n\nConstructive notice also applies to published laws and regulations (everyone is presumed to know the law), corporate filings (articles of incorporation, UCC financing statements), and court filings. The doctrine prevents people from profiting by claiming ignorance of facts they could have discovered through reasonable diligence.",
