    explanation: "The counterparts clause is one of the most practical provisions in modern contract law. It allows parties to sign separate copies of the same document, and each signed copy is treated as an original. Together, all counterparts constitute one and the same agreement.\n\nThis provision became essential with the rise of remote business transactions. Before counterparts clauses were common, all parties typically had to sign the same physical document, which could involve shipping a single copy around the world for signatures.\n\nToday, counterparts clauses routinely include language permitting electronic signatures and transmission by email, PDF, or other electronic means. This aligns with the Electronic Signatures in Global and National Commerce Act (E-SIGN) and the Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (UETA), which give electronic signatures the same legal effect as handwritten ones in most circumstances.",
