    term: "Cross-Default",
    category: "Financial",
    definition: "A provision in a loan or contract stating that a default under one agreement automatically triggers a default under another related agreement between the same or related parties.",
    explanation: "Cross-default clauses are primarily used in lending and financial agreements. They protect creditors by ensuring that if a borrower defaults on one obligation, all related obligations become immediately due as well. This prevents a borrower from selectively defaulting on one loan while continuing to pay others.\n\nFor example, a company might have a $5 million revolving credit facility and a $10 million term loan with the same bank. A cross-default clause would mean that defaulting on either loan triggers a default on both. This gives the bank the right to accelerate both loans and demand immediate full payment.\n\nCross-default clauses can also extend across different creditors. A bond indenture might include a cross-default provision triggered by default on bank loans, effectively creating a domino effect. Borrowers should be careful to negotiate thresholds (minimum default amounts) and cure periods to prevent minor or technical defaults from cascading across all agreements.",
