    explanation: "De facto is a Latin term meaning 'in fact' or 'in practice.' It's used to describe situations that exist in reality, regardless of whether they've been officially or legally established. The opposite term is de jure, meaning 'by law' or 'by right.'\n\nIn corporate law, a de facto corporation is one that hasn't met all legal requirements for incorporation but operates as if it were a corporation. Courts may recognize it to prevent injustice to third parties who dealt with it in good faith.\n\nIn employment law, someone might be a de facto employee even though they're classified as an independent contractor — courts look at the actual working relationship, not just the label. In family law, de facto relationships (common-law marriages or domestic partnerships) may receive legal recognition in some jurisdictions.\n\nThe de facto doctrine is important because it prevents parties from exploiting technical legal deficiencies to avoid their obligations.",
