    definition: "A contractual clause that designates the specific court, jurisdiction, or location where any disputes arising from the contract must be litigated.",
    explanation: "Forum selection clauses specify where disputes will be resolved. They can designate a particular state, county, or even a specific court. These clauses provide predictability and allow parties to plan for potential litigation in a known venue.\n\nForum selection clauses come in two forms. Mandatory clauses require that disputes be litigated exclusively in the designated forum. Permissive clauses simply consent to jurisdiction in the designated forum but don't prevent litigation elsewhere.\n\nThe Supreme Court's decision in M/S Bremen v. Zapata Oil established that forum selection clauses are presumptively valid and enforceable unless the resisting party can show that enforcement would be unreasonable or unjust, or that the clause was procured through fraud or overreaching.\n\nFor businesses operating across state lines or internationally, forum selection clauses are crucial. Without one, disputes could potentially be filed in any jurisdiction where either party operates, leading to expensive and inconvenient litigation in an unfamiliar court.",
