    explanation: "The statute of frauds is a centuries-old legal requirement that certain important contracts must be in writing to be enforceable. Originally enacted in England in 1677 to prevent fraud and perjury, every U.S. state has adopted some version of it.\n\nContracts typically covered by the statute of frauds include: contracts for the sale or transfer of land or interests in land; contracts that cannot be performed within one year from the date of making; contracts for the sale of goods worth $500 or more (under the UCC); promises to pay another person's debt (suretyship); promises made in consideration of marriage; and contracts by an executor to pay estate debts from personal funds.\n\nThe writing requirement doesn't mean the contract must be a formal document. Courts have accepted letters, emails, text messages, and even napkins as sufficient writings, as long as they contain the essential terms and are signed by the party against whom enforcement is sought.\n\nThere are exceptions. Part performance (beginning to perform the contract) can take an oral contract out of the statute of frauds in some circumstances, particularly for real estate.",
